<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="552" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,152,611]" pageId="3" pageNumber="552">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,297,323]" pageId="3" pageNumber="552">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is a concatenation of the Latin 
<emphasis box="[917,993,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="552">alia ex</emphasis>
meaning ‘different from’ and 
<emphasis box="[1334,1407,298,323]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="552">striata</emphasis>
in reference to this species not being identical with 
<emphasis box="[699,806,334,359]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="552">H. striata</emphasis>
Yang &amp; Yang. It is used as a noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="552" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,152,611]" pageId="3" pageNumber="552">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,369,395]" pageId="3" pageNumber="552">Remarks.</emphasis>
The markings on the scutum of this species somewhat resemble those of 
<emphasis box="[1134,1252,370,395]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="552">H. acutata</emphasis>
Grootaert, Yang &amp; Saigusa (in which the width and intensity of the median dark stripe varies greatly) or even 
<emphasis box="[1179,1336,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="552">H. systoechon</emphasis>
Plant (in which the dark scutal marking is usually very broad with diffuse edges) from which it may readily be separated by the male terminalia. A generally similarly broad cercus with bluntly pointed dorsoapical and ventroapical processes suggests close affinities with two extralimital species, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Fallen)" baseAuthorityName="Fallen" box="[769,995,513,540]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Tachydromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="552" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oratoria">
